<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1922-05-10T08:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1922-05-10T08:00:00-05:00" n="677" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d677">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">550.E1/260: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Italy</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Child</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><seg rendition="#center">[Paraphrase]</seg></opener>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Genoa</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1922-05-10T14:00:00+01:00"><hi rend="italic">May 10,
                                        1922—2 p.m.</hi></date><lb/>[Received May 10—1
                                p.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>39. It now seems that no one is satisfied with clause 7 of the memorandum
                            to the Soviet delegation. Under the supervision of the British and
                            Italian delegates, it is being redrawn. As instructed, I made it clear
                            several days ago to the delegations of France, Great Britain and Italy
                            that clause 7 was not in accord with our views regarding the protection
                            to be given to private property rights.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Child</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>